(2) Annotations - write *why* you are doing things, not just *what* the code does - easier to figure out the technical side later if you forget, but you won't figure out the past motivation as easily #rstats #phdchat
(1) I use prefixes for my scripts: load, clean, do, fig (for figures), mod (for models), fun (for functions) #rstats #phdchat

So, there's a line-up of values (strings or numbers or Boolean) in a vector. At any given time, you can imagine them being in a single column line-up of data in #Excel should you want to be familiar with it. #rstats #noob #LeaData

In summary: vector is a set of data of the same type, lined in a single dimensional direction (it is easier for me to imagine what was taught to me in modern maths). Eg. lea_shoes <- c('Gucci', 'Bata', 'Jimmy Choo') OR lea_money <- c(100, 320, 1071) #rstats #noob #LeaData

Have you used #rstats Biostring's local alignment? It's a similarity metric that rewards similarity without punishing for irrelevant differences. Levenshtein punishes for irrelevant differences. I've had really good success with local alignment. See here: https:// ro-che.info/articles/2016- 12-11-local-alignment …
